{{refimprove|date=November 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Andrey Soloviev | image = Soloviev-andrey.jpg | alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software --> | caption = Andrey Soloviev | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = 1953 | birth_place = | death_date = September 27, 1993 | death_place = Sukhumi | nationality = Russian | other_names = | occupation = War photographer | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''Andrey Borisovich Soloviev''' ({{lang-ru|Андрей Борисович Соловьёв}}) (1953 &ndash; September 27, 1993) was a Russian [[war]] [[photographer]].
He was killed by [[sniper]] fire while covering the battle for [[Sukhumi]] in [[War in Abkhazia (1992–1993)|Abkhazian war]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cpj.org/killed/1993/andrei-soloviev.php |title= Andrei Soloviev entry in the registry of killed journalists maintained by the Committee to Protect Journalists (CPJ)|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website= Committee to Protect Journalists |access-date=17 February 2017}}</ref>
Soloviev studied at the [[MArchI|Moscow Institute of Architecture]] but never graduated. Instead, he became a [[Photojournalism|photojournalist]], joining the [[Telegraph Agency of the Soviet Union|Itar-TASS]] news agency in 1987. He also worked as a stringer for the [[Associated Press]].
After the break-up of the [[Soviet Union]], Andrey Soloviev covered many armed conflicts, including in [[Nagorno-Karabakh]], [[Transnistria]], [[Tajikistan]], [[Uzbekistan]], [[South Ossetia]]. He also filmed the aftermath of the [[1988 Armenian earthquake]], the collapse of the regime of [[Nicolae Ceauşescu]], and was in [[Iraq]] during the [[Gulf War]].
His photographs received numerous awards, including the [[World Press Photo]] prize.
