{{italic title}}[[File:Frontispiece of the 1779 edition of Voltaire’s ‘Dialogues d’Evhémère’.jpg|thumb|Frontispiece of the 1779 edition of Voltaire’s ‘Dialogues d’Evhémère’]] '' ''' Les Dialogues d’Evhémère''' '' ('The Dialogues of [[Euhemerus]]') is a little-known philosophical dialogue by [[Voltaire]], published in 1777. At the time of its writing he was 83 years old and knew that he was coming to the end of his life:<ref name="Vermeer"/> the work is a kind of philosophical testament. Like many other works by Voltaire, it is written in the tradition of Socratic dialogue, where the interlocutors seek the truth together.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Banderier |first1=Gilles |title=Voltaire en dialogues |journal=Acta fabula |date=May 2006 |volume=7 |issue=2 |url=http://www.fabula.org/acta/document1332.php |accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>
==Arguments== The imagined dialogue takes place between two historical figures, Euhemerus and Callicrates. Euhemerus, a [[Stoic]], was a contemporary of [[Alexander the Great]], remembered mostly for his view that the Classical Greek gods had originally been people, deified long after their deaths by their followers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Meurger |first1=Michel |title=Evhémère et les monstres. Croyances populaires et interprétation instruite |url=https://www.hommes-et-faits.com/lime/MMeurger_Monsters_.htm |website=Hommes et faits.com |accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref> Callicrates was also a philosopher, from the third century BC, of whom little is known but whom Voltaire makes an [[Epicurean]]. His views, including [[atheism]], are meant to represent the views of Voltaire's contemporaries [[Holbach]], [[La Mettrie]] and [[Diderot]].
In the dialogue as in historic reality Euhemeros had enjoyed a life of travel, much of it following Alexander; Callicrates is curious to know what his friend has learned as a result of these experiences. The conversations that follow are set out in twelve dialogues:<ref name="Vermeer">{{cite book |last1=Vermeer-Pardoen |first1=Hannie |title=Voltaire De dialogen van Euhemeros Het nut van de filosofie |date=2017 |publisher=Gennep B.V., Uitgeverij Van |location=Amsterdam |isbn=978-9461648594 |url=https://cbonline.boekhuis.nl/pls/cover/p_get_cover_fe?p_hash=0030284E59D1F5E446B902E37A7BB78D |accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>{{rp|7–8}}
{{columns-list|colwidth=35em| * '' '''First dialogue''' '' - on Alexander the Great * '' '''Second dialogue''' '' - on the Divinity * '' '''Third dialogue''' '' - on the philosophy of Epicurus and Greek theology * '' '''Fourth dialogue''' '' - on whether an active God would be more worthwhile than the gods of Epicurus, who do nothing * '' '''Fifth dialogue''' '' - poor people who dig in the abyss. Instinct, the basis for all animal action * '' '''Sixth dialogue''' '' - did Plato and Aristotle Aristote teach us about God and how the world was made? * '' '''Seventh dialogue''' '' - on the philosophers who have flourished among the barbarians * '' '''Eighth dialogue''' '' - great discoveries by barbarian philosophers; the Greeks are no more than children compared to them * '' '''Ninth dialogue''' '' - on procreation * '' '''Tenth dialogue''' '' - on whether the earth was formed by a comet * '' '''Eleventh dialogue''' '' - on whether the mountains were formed by the sea * '' '''Twelfth dialogue''' '' - on the inventions of barbarians: new arts, new ideas.<ref name="Wikisource">{{cite web |last1=Voltaire |first1=François-Marie Arouet |title=Dialogues d’Évhémère/Édition Garnier |url=https://fr.m.wikisource.org/wiki/Dialogues_d%E2%80%99%C3%89vh%C3%A9m%C3%A8re/%C3%89dition_Garnier |website=fr.wikisource.org |accessdate=9 November 2018}}</ref> }}
There are two main themes in the dialogues. The first six consider metaphysical questions such as whether we have a soul, whether God exists and, if he does, who is responsible for all the misery on earth. And the last six dialogues are about natural philosophy and the material world - what we know about the cosmos, the earth, the creation of mountains, and the generation of new life. What all the dialogues have in common is an appeal for modesty and restraint in argument. There is little we can undubitably know and much is hidden from us. For this reason, whatever we may believe, we should never ignore evidence or assumptions from outside the universe of our beliefs; rather than proclaiming dogmas we should engage in dialogue. At the same time, Euhemerus is unsparing in his attacks on atheists, atomists and materialists as well as on religious dogma - all of which he terms 'madness, misery and crime'.<ref>{{cite web |last1=de Baar |first1=Marinus |title=Niets dan waanzin, ellende en misdaad |url=https://www.trouw.nl/home/niets-dan-waanzin-ellende-en-misdaad~a275ddc5/ |website=trouw.nl |publisher=de Persgroep Nederland B.V. |accessdate=10 November 2018}}</ref>
The dialogues offer an overview of Voltaire's life of thought. Euhemerus is effectively Voltaire's mouthpiece; he has seen the follies, delusions and misery of mankind. Much of the dialogue focuses on paradox of God's goodness and the misery on earth. Euhemerus draws hope from scientific progress that points to a future world built on rationality. Eventually Callicrates decides to embark on a journey of his own to the barbarian lands from which his friend had learned so much.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dialogues d'Evhémère - Voltaire (1779) |url=https://www.boekmeter.nl/book/38450 |website=Boekmeter.nl |accessdate=10 November 2018}}</ref>
==Censorship and the first edition== Voltaire's 94-page autographed manuscript still survives (pages 37–40 are not in his hand).<ref>{{cite web |title=Receuil factice d'ouvrages et fragments autographes de Voltaire |url=http://w3public.ville-ge.ch/bge/volage.nsf/Attachments/ms01frameset.htm/$file/ms01.pdf |website=w3public.ville-ge.ch|publisher=Bibliothèque de Genève, Institut et Musée Voltaire |accessdate=9 November 2018}}</ref> However Voltaire's surviving correspondence makes no reference to the work, its development, or the ideas it elaborates.<ref name="Cairn">{{cite journal |last1=Paillard |first1=Christophe |title=La correspondance de Voltaire et l’édition de ses œuvres. problème de méthodologie éditoriale |journal=Revue d'Histoire Litteraire de la France |date=2012 |volume=112 |pages=859–872 |doi=10.3917/rhlf.124.0859 |url=https://www.cairn.info/revue-d-histoire-litteraire-de-la-france-2012-4-page-859.htm |accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref> Likewise [[Friedrich Melchior, Baron von Grimm|Grimm]] does not mention it. The ''[[Mémoires secrets]]'' from November 1777 did refer to the work however, and a comment from [[Jean-Louis Wagnière]] indicated that the ''Dialogues'' had been published only shortly before.<ref>{{cite book|title=Oeuvres de Voltaire avec préfaces, avvertissement, notes ... par m. Beuchot: Mélanges. Tome 14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t1WHuzF7XrQC&pg=PA146|year=1834|publisher=Lefèvre|page=146}}</ref>
Over the course of his life Voltaire had had his works condemned or banned by royal censors in France on many occasions. He also had a number of ways of avoiding censorship - including arranging for his work to be printed outside France, and having it printed anonymously so he could deny authorship.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Birkenstock |first1=Jane |title=Château de Cirey, Residence of Voltaire |url=http://www.visitvoltaire.com/voltaire_bio.htm |website=www.visitvoltaire.com |publisher=Château de Cirey |accessdate=9 November 2018}}</ref><ref name="Davidson2012">{{cite book|author=Ian Davidson|title=Voltaire: A Life|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hFU0CgAAQBAJ&pg=PT32|date=12 March 2012|publisher=Pegasus Books|isbn=978-1-68177-039-0|pages=32–}}</ref> Indeed, the presentation of challenging or radical ideas in the form of a dialogue was one method of bringing unconventional ideas to public attention while being less likely to have the word altered or suppressed.<ref name="Collins2015">{{cite book|author=James Daniel Collins|title=Interpreting Modern Philosophy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=olt9BgAAQBAJ&pg=PA87|date=8 March 2015|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-6788-2|page=87}}</ref>
The frontispiece of the first known edition of the ''Dialogues d'Evhémère'' indicates that it was published in London by Voltaire not in 1777 as suggested by the ''Mémoires secrets'' but in 1779 (i.e. the year after Voltaire's death), but does not name a publisher. In fact it is evident from the distinctive typography used that it was printed not in London but in [[Lausanne]], by Abraham-Louis Tarin, who worked for the publisher François Grasset.<ref>{{cite web |title=Livre Dialogues d'Evhémère / par M. de Voltaire |url=https://explore.rero.ch/fr_CH/rero/result/L/VlRMU19SRVJPUjAwNDMzMzQ5NQ== |website=explore.rero.ch |publisher=Réseau des bibliothèques de Suisse occidentale |accessdate=9 November 2018}}</ref> Grasset is noted for having previously published a number of works attacking Voltaire as well as for having on several occasions clashed with him over the intended publication of Voltaire's works from unauthorised manuscript versions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chatelard |first1=Marie-Claire |title=François GRASSET (1722-1789) |url=http://dictionnaire-journalistes.gazettes18e.fr/journaliste/359-francois-grasset |website=dictionnaire-journalistes.gazettes18e.fr |publisher=IHRIM UMR & ISH USR |accessdate=9 November 2018}}</ref>
